running out of time?

1199
01:06:43,940 --> 01:06:46,560
Write day and night like you're
running out of time?

1200
01:06:46,560 --> 01:06:49,080
Ev'ry day you fight, like you're
running out of time

1201
01:06:49,120 --> 01:06:52,060
Keep on fighting. In the meantime--
(Non-stop!)

1202
01:06:52,100 --> 01:06:55,000
HAMILTON:
Corruption's such an old song that
we can sing along in harmony

1203
01:06:55,000 --> 01:06:59,520
And nowhere is it stronger than in Albany
This colony's economy's increasingly stalling

1204
01:06:59,520 --> 01:07:02,600
And honestly, that's why public service (He's just)
Seems to be calling me. (Non-stop!)

1205
01:07:02,600 --> 01:07:04,980
I practiced the law,
I practic'ly perfected it

1206
01:07:04,980 --> 01:07:07,460
I've seen injustice in the world
and I've corrected it

1207
01:07:07,460 --> 01:07:10,600
Now for a strong central democracy
If not, then I'll be Socrates

1208
01:07:10,600 --> 01:07:12,660
Throwing verbal rocks
At these mediocrities.

1209
01:07:12,660 --> 01:07:15,300
BURR:
Hamilton, at the Constitutional Convention:

1210
01:07:15,300 --> 01:07:17,900
HAMILTON:
I was chosen for the Constitutional Convention

1211
01:07:17,900 --> 01:07:20,500
BURR:
There as a New York junior delegate:

1212
01:07:20,500 --> 01:07:23,180
HAMILTON:
Now what I'm going to say may sound indelicate...

1213
01:07:23,180 --> 01:07:25,720
BURR:
Goes and proposes his own form of government!

1214
01:07:25,720 --> 01:07:28,080
(What?)
His own plan for a new form of government!

1215
01:07:28,080 --> 01:07:30,920
(What?)
Talks for six hours! The convention is listless!

1216
01:07:30,920 --> 01:07:33,640
Bright young man...
Yo, who the f is this?

1217
01:07:33,640 --> 01:07:38,460
Why do you always say what you believe?
Why do you always say what you believe?

1218
01:07:38,460 --> 01:07:43,980
Ev'ry proclamation guarantees
free ammunition for your enemies!

1219
01:07:43,980 --> 01:07:46,600
Why do you write like it's
going out of style?

1220
01:07:46,600 --> 01:07:48,880
Write day and night like it's
going out of style?

1221
01:07:48,880 --> 01:07:51,880
Ev'ry day you fight like it's
Going out of style

1222
01:07:51,880 --> 01:07:53,140
Do what you do

1223
01:07:54,920 --> 01:07:56,460
BURR: Alexander?
HAMILTON: Aaron Burr, sir

1224
01:07:56,460 --> 01:07:57,820
BURR:
It's the middle of the night

1225
01:07:57,820 --> 01:07:59,020
HAMILTON:
Can we confer, sir?

1226
01:07:59,020 --> 01:08:00,200
BURR:
Is this a legal matter?

1227
01:08:00,200 --> 01:08:01,780
HAMILTON:
Yes, and it's important to me

1228
01:08:01,780 --> 01:08:02,580
BURR:
What do you need?

1229
01:08:02,580 --> 01:08:04,360
HAMILTON:
Burr, you're a better lawyer than me

1230
01:08:04,360 --> 01:08:05,080
BURR:
Okay

1231
01:08:05,080 --> 01:08:07,080
HAMILTON:
I know I talk too much, I'm abrasive

1232
01:08:07,080 --> 01:08:09,820
You're incredible in court,
You're succinct, persuasive.

1233
01:08:09,820 --> 01:08:12,420
My client needs a strong defense.
You're the solution.

1234
01:08:12,420 --> 01:08:13,200
BURR:
Who's your client?

1235
01:08:13,200 --> 01:08:15,200
HAMILTON:
The new U.S. Constitution

1236
01:08:15,200 --> 01:08:15,620
BURR:
No

1237
01:08:15,620 --> 01:08:16,140
HAMILTON:
Hear me out

1238
01:08:16,140 --> 01:08:17,020
BURR:
No way!

1239
01:08:17,020 --> 01:08:19,680
HAMILTON:
A series of essays, anonymously published

1240
01:08:19,680 --> 01:08:21,660
Defending the document to the public

1241
01:08:21,660 --> 01:08:23,280
BURR: No one will read it
HAMILTON: I disagree

1242
01:08:23,280 --> 01:08:25,220
BURR:And if it fails?
HAMILTON: Burr, that's why we need it

1243
01:08:25,220 --> 01:08:28,000
BURR: The constitution's a mess
HAMILTON: So it needs amendments

1244
01:08:28,000 --> 01:08:30,640
BURR: It's full of contradictions
HAMILTON: So is independence

1245
01:08:30,640 --> 01:08:32,080
We have to start somewhere

1246
01:08:32,080 --> 01:08:34,480
BURR: No. No way
HAMILTON: You're making a mistake

1247
01:08:34,480 --> 01:08:35,820
BURR: Good night
HAMILTON: Hey

1248
01:08:35,820 --> 01:08:38,720
What are you waiting for?
What do you stall for?

1249
01:08:38,720 --> 01:08:39,980
BURR: What?
HAMILTON: We won the war

1250
01:08:39,980 --> 01:08:43,020
What was it all for?
Do you support this constitution?

1251
01:08:43,020 --> 01:08:44,400
BURR: Of course
HAMILTON: Then defend it

1252
01:08:44,400 --> 01:08:46,340
BURR:
And what if you're backing the wrong horse?

1253
01:08:46,340 --> 01:08:49,000
HAMILTON:
Burr, we studied and we fought and we killed

1254
01:08:49,000 --> 01:08:51,640
For the notion of a nation
we now get to build

1255
01:08:51,640 --> 01:08:54,280
For once in your life,
take a stand with pride

1256
01:08:54,280 --> 01:08:56,600
I don't understand how
you stand to the side

1257
01:08:56,600 --> 01:09:00,560
BURR:
I'll keep all my plans close to my chest

1258
01:09:00,560 --> 01:09:04,080
(Wait for it, wait for it, wait for it)
I'll wait here and see

1259
01:09:04,080 --> 01:09:06,820
Which way the wind will blow

1260
01:09:06,820 --> 01:09:14,240
I'm taking my time watching the afterbirth
of a nation watching the tension grow.

1261
01:09:18,220 --> 01:09:19,860
ANGELICA:
I am sailing off to London.

1262
01:09:19,860 --> 01:09:23,440
I'm accompanied by someone who always pays

1263
01:09:23,440 --> 01:09:28,640
I have found a wealthy husband who will
keep me in comfort for all my days

1264
01:09:28,640 --> 01:09:34,080
He is not a lot of fun, but there's no one
who can match you for turn of phrase

1265
01:09:34,080 --> 01:09:36,340
My Alexander

1266
01:09:36,340 --> 01:09:37,460
HAMILTON:
Angelica

1267
01:09:37,460 --> 01:09:40,160
ANGELICA:
Don't forget to write

1268
01:09:40,160 --> 01:09:42,600
ELIZA:
Look at where you are

1269
01:09:42,760 --> 01:09:47,500
Look at where you started
The fact that you're alive is a miracle

1270
01:09:47,500 --> 01:09:50,500
Just stay alive, that would be enough

1271
01:09:50,980 --> 01:09:55,760
And if your wife could share
a fraction of your time

1272
01:09:55,760 --> 01:10:00,140
If I could grant you peace of mind
Would that be enough?

1273
01:10:00,820 --> 01:10:05,280
BURR:
Alexander joins forces with James Madison
and John Jay to write a series of essays

1274
01:10:05,280 --> 01:10:09,700
Defending the new United States Constitution,
entitled The Federalist Papers.

1275
